# Git & GitHub Overview

# Git -> is a distributed version control system that tracks code changes using commits.
Each developer has a full copy of the repository and its history.

# GitHub -> is a collaboration platform built on top of Git.
It provides remote repositories, Pull Requests (PRs), code reviews, CI/CD integration, and branch protection.

# Commits & SHA
A commit is a snapshot of the project at a specific point in time.
Each commit is identified by a SHA (Secure Hash Algorithm), also called a commit hash.
Example:
a3f5c9b

# A SHA is generated from:
File contents
Commit message
Author and timestamp
Parent commit

📌 Any change creates a new SHA.
Git identifies changes by SHA, not by code similarity.

# Squash & Merge
Squash & Merge combines all commits from a source branch into one single commit before merging.
Example:
A: add feature
B: fix issue
C: cleanup

After squash:
S: add feature


# Creates a new commit with a new SHA
Original commit history is not preserved
Target branch stays clean and readable
When to Use Squash & Merge
Feature branches
Small or self-contained changes
Keeping main / develop history clean
When NOT to Use Squash & Merge
Long-running branches (develop, uat, main)
Environment promotion branches

# Recommended Practice
feature/* → develop (Squash & Merge)
develop   → uat     (Normal Merge)
uat       → main    (Normal Merge)

# Key Takeaway
Git tracks history using commit SHAs.
Squash & Merge cleans history but removes commit ancestry, so it should be used carefully.


# squash & merge can be handled safely, even with long-running branches, if you follow the right rules.
The key is how you handle hotfixes and branch syncing.

# Below is a clear, practical explanation you can also adapt for documentation.
Short Answer
✔ Yes, squash & merge is easy if there are no hotfixes
✔ Yes, it is still safe if hotfixes are always down-merged correctly
❌ Problems start when hotfixes are not back-merged

# Case 1: No Hotfixes (Safest Case)
Flow
feature/* → develop (Squash)
develop   → uat     (Normal merge)
uat       → main    (Normal merge)

Why This Works
Changes move in one direction
Commit ancestry is preserved between environment branches
Squash happens only at the feature level
✅ No conflicts
✅ Clean history
✅ Easy releases

# Case 2: Hotfix Exists (Most Real Projects)
Correct Way to Handle Hotfixes
hotfix/* → main     (Squash or Normal)
main     → uat      (Normal merge)
uat      → develop  (Normal merge)


📌 This is called down-merging
Why Down-Merging Is Mandatory
Hotfix changes must exist in all lower environments.
If you skip down-merge:
develop does not know about the fix
Future merges re-introduce bugs
Same change appears with different SHAs
Conflicts are guaranteed
Visual Example (Correct)
hotfix/H
   ↓
 main
   ↓
  uat
   ↓
develop


✔ Same commit flows through all branches
✔ Git recognizes commit ancestry
✔ No duplicate changes

# What NOT to Do (Very Common Mistake)
hotfix → main
feature → develop
develop → uat → main

❌ Hotfix never reached develop
❌ Develop reintroduces bug
❌ Conflicts during merge
❌ History divergence